It looks like the issue is with how you&#39;re sending the `phNos` data in the `FormData` object. When you send `fdata.append(&quot;phNos&quot;, [{id:1,phNo:&quot;12345&quot;}])`, Spring is interpreting that as a single `PhoneNumber` object with the properties `id` and `phNo` set to the string &quot;[object Object]&quot;.
Instead you can try converting the data in javascript before appending it to the FormData object.
You can use JSON.stringify() to convert the data to a string format before appending it to the FormData object.

    fdata.append(&quot;phNos&quot;, JSON.stringify([{id:1,phNo:&quot;12345&quot;}]));

Also, update the content type header when sending the request.


        fetch(&quot;/save/c&quot;, {
        body: fdata,
        method: &quot;post&quot;,
        headers: {
            &#39;Content-Type&#39;: &#39;application/json&#39;
        }
    }).then((response) =&gt; {
        //Somecode  
    });


This way you don&#39;t need to deserialize it on the server side and Spring will map the data to your ContactDetail class automatically.

Also, you can remove the parameterized constructor from PhoneNumber class and use `@JsonCreator` and `@JsonProperty` to deserialize it.

